<HL>
   It's a Nice Place to Live, but They
   Just Don't Want to Visit There
   ----
   By Alecia Swasy
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   If you're looking for a rustic summer vacation, West
Virginia has a few vacancies these days.
   That's because the Mountain State got cut from a "Third
World in the U.S." tour of Appalachia. The reason: West
Virginia is too remote, even for this tour.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Global Exchange, the San Francisco group that organized
the tour, says it would take too long to get to West
Virginia. Besides, local officials weren't exactly receptive
to a group that compares their state to the Third World.
   "If they're looking for the Third World, they don't have
to leave the state of California," grouses John H. Brown Jr.,
West Virginia's commissioner of tourism and parks. "They've
got more poor people in the barrios of Los Angeles than we
have in the whole state."
   West Virginia officials suggested that the group skip the
southern coal fields, a depressed region, and focus on the
state's scenic charms: lakes, mountains and golf courses.
"They suggested we come and go white-water rafting," says
Laurie Adams, tour planner.
   No dice. These are reality tours, says Ms. Adams. So the
10-day trip, which began yesterday, will skip West Virginia
and focus on Kentucky, Tennessee and Virginia. Nine people,
including a teacher, a convention planner and a film maker,
have signed up for the $500 excursion to coal mines, farms
and rural households.
   So West Virginia feels a bit left out. "I'm disappointed,"
says Mr. Brown. "I didn't mean to keep them from coming."
   Folks in the states still left on the itinerary express
mixed feelings about the tour. Ms. Adams has received some
nasty letters and irate phone calls from residents who are
fed up with the stereotypes of their mountain communities.
"One person wrote to say she never married her cousin and has
used an outhouse only once," says Ms. Adams.
   For their part, Kentucky officials say they welcome any
visitors to the Bluegrass State. Jim Carroll, a state tourism
spokesman, considers the tour's name offensive, but "we
haven't taken it too seriously."
   Personally, he questions the premise of a so-called
reality tour by these city slickers from the West: "Reality
in San Francisco is an oxymoron," he jokes.
   But Mr. Carroll says Kentucky officials might turn out to
greet the out-of-towners. "We just hope we have enough time
to put on our shoes and kick the pigs out of the yard before
they get here."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0146
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0146.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Bush Vetoes Bill
   That Would Relax
   Hatch Act's Curbs
   ----
   By Michel McQueen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- President Bush vetoed a bill that would ease
restrictions on political activity by federal civil servants,
saying the change would "inevitably lead to repoliticizing
the federal work force."
   Mr. Bush's veto, which was expected, was his 12th since he
took office. All his previous vetoes have been sustained;
most recently, the Senate last week sustained his veto of an
Amtrak authorization bill by two votes. Mr. Bush is also
expected to veto a measure passed by Congress late Thursday
that would guarantee workers as much as 12 weeks' unpaid
leave for childbirth, adoption or serious family illnesses.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In rejecting the measure to lift restrictions on federal
workers' campaign activities, Mr. Bush said the current
system protects workers from harassment and ensures the
integrity and neutrality of the federal work force. Since
1939, the so-called Hatch Act has barred federal workers from
most partisan political activity aside from voting, including
holding partisan political positions or participating in
campaigns. Federal workers can, however, participate in
non-partisan activities such as school board races.
   Labor leaders and representatives from jurisdictions with
a substantial federal work force pressed for the changes,
saying three million federal and postal workers should have
the same rights as other citizens. The changes approved by
Congress last week, by a vote of 334-87 in the House and
67-30 in the Senate, would allow federal and postal workers
to hold positions in the political parties, to attend party
conventions as delegates and to raise money from fellow
members of the same union.
   Although the original votes in both houses were large
enough to override Mr. Bush's veto, GOP leaders have
expressed confidence they can muster the votes in the Senate
to sustain the veto.
   Meanwhile, some Republicans are urging Mr. Bush not to
follow through on his threat to veto the parental-leave bill.
"I would hope the First Father wouldn't make this decision
without first hearing from Republicans who support the bill,"
said Rep. Marge Roukema (R., N.J.). "There are reasons why
business should be concerned about intrusive new mandates,
but this isn't one of them."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
