<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0145
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0145.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Rate of Inflation
   In Britain Rose
   To 9.7% in May
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Britain's annual rate of inflation rose more
than expected to 9.7% in May from 9.4% in April.
   The so-called underlying rate, which by excluding
mortgage-interest payments and the recently introduced
"community charge" is more comparable with European inflation
measures, rose to 7% from 6.5%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A Treasury spokeswoman said the inflation rise, which was
caused by increased food and clothing prices and the residual
impact of higher excise duties on tobacco and alcohol prices,
is "not very welcome."
   Economists warned that the rise in the underlying level
indicates that inflationary pressures are even more
entrenched than expected, and that will make it even more
difficult for the government to achieve the economic
conditions it has set for taking the British pound into the
exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System.
   The government has repeatedly said that it won't take that
step until British inflation is down closer to European
levels. Although it remains unclear exactly what inflation
measure the government will use in making its judgment,
Chancellor of the Exchequer John Major has said that an
underlying level will be used.
   Stephen Hannah, head of research at Natwest Capital
Markets, predicted that the underlying inflation rate won't
fall toward European inflation levels until early next year.
"If we take the government at its word," sterling probably
won't be able to join the exchange rate mechanism until the
spring, he said.
   Sterling rose sharply last week on speculation that the
government is considering taking sterling into the mechanism
as early as this autumn, but it slipped back after the
inflation report was released.
   The rise in the annual rate of inflation, as measured by
the retail price index, was higher than the 9.5% average of
economists' forecasts and took the rate back up to its
highest level since March 1982, when it was at 10.4%.
   The 0.5-point increase in the underlying rate took it to
its highest level since October 1982, when it was also at 7%.
   Steven Bell, chief economist at Morgan Grenfell &amp; Co.,
said price rises in clothing and food confirm that the
country is facing continued demand-led inflation. Retail
sales figures last week indicated that consumer spending
remains buoyant despite the government's tight-money policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0144
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0144.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   As Aetna Adds
   Flextime, Bosses
   Learn to Cope
   ----
   By Carol Hymowitz
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   AET LABOR
</CO>
<LP>
   HARTFORD, Conn. -- It's 8 a.m. Monday and Aetna Life &amp;
Casualty Co. employees, once a lockstep army, are marching to
their own tune.
   And the weekly maneuvers begin for managers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A corporate meeting planner arrives to find an employee he
didn't expect to see until Wednesday busily organizing her
desk; she's switched places with her job-sharing partner, who
usually works Mondays. A finance manager calls a department
meeting, then cancels it after realizing two part-timers
won't be in until Tuesday. And a data processing manager
ponders how her department of six will function when three
employees, all expecting babies, take six-week family leaves.
   Faced with a tight labor market, Aetna is rewriting its
rules to give employees more say in when, where and how much
they work. While other companies are beginning to do the
same, Aetna seems to be on the vanguard. And a look at what
the insurer is doing shows some of the benefits and the
pitfalls of breaking away from workweek rigidity.
   The new flexibility means difficult adjustments for
managers. Suddenly they must negotiate an array of work
schedules, supervise "out of sight" subordinates and assuage
traditional nine-to-fivers who may resent their freewheeling
colleagues.
   "You can no longer say `this is the way it's always been
done' and expect that to continue," says Barbara Prescott,
director of health claims. Nearly 40% of her 107 employees
now work "flextime" (adjusting their own starting and
quitting hours), while others work part-time or from home.
"Today's work force is fluid," she notes. "You've got to give
up some control and be open to new ideas -- but also realize
you aren't going to please everyone."
   Daniel Durej, director of financial services-commercial
insurance division, admits "a chill went through me" when a
manager on his staff requested a part-time schedule after the
birth of her second child two years ago. "My first response
was `we can't do it,'" he says. "I thought maybe if we were
standing on an assembly line making widgets it would be
possible, but this is a management job."
   But the alternative -- losing a highly valued employee --
seemed worse. So Mr. Durej offered her a three-day-a-week,
nonmanagement job. Still, he adds, he probably assigned her
too many duties for a part-time schedule, and "she ended up
taking work home a lot, working overtime and feeling
overburdened."
   He, in turn, found himself "stepping in too often" to
absorb some of the load. The solution: putting a layer of
management between himself and the part-timer.
   Despite the snags, Mr. Durej became "less apprehensive"
about flexible scheduling. When a second manager requested a
four-day week after the birth of her third child, he didn't
immediately rule out a management slot. Instead, he polled
her staff, who agreed they'd have no problem working for a
part-time boss. But to ensure that they wouldn't be
overworked, he added one more employee to her staff.
   The biggest fear among managers is that once they say yes
to one employee, everyone will want part-time or job sharing.
After Vin Darcy, a systems supervisor, arranged a three-day
schedule for a woman who was juggling caring for a new baby
and her two elderly parents, he heard "me too" rumblings from
others on his staff. "I called them together and said `you
know you'd have to take a pay cut' if you work fewer days --
and they all backed off," he says.
   Mr. Darcy isn't at all certain he'd offer part-time
equally to everyone. "It takes a very strong person to do
this," he says. Two women on his staff who currently work
compressed weeks "do as much in three days as others do in
five."
   Still, the success of such arrangements has propelled
Aetna to offer employees a medley of options. Some 1,200
employees now work part time, up from 700 a few years ago;
several hundred telecommute from their homes and 65 to 70
work part-time in pairs, sharing one job, one salary and one
set of benefits.
   "We're not doing it to be nice, but because it makes
business sense," says Sherry Herchenroether, manager of
family services. Nearly 70% of Aetna's 45,000 employees are
female, including 17% of the company's managers. Three years
ago, Aetna found that 23% of those who had taken maternity
disability left the company after becoming mothers. A year
later, after introducing a six-month unpaid family leave,
that attrition rate was cut in half.
   The hardest thing to manage is job sharing. "You have to
match the right people together, and you're supervising two
people for the time it would take to supervise one," Ms.
Herchenroether says.
   Sue Yucha and Karen Queno for the past four years have
shared a job arranging conferences for Aetna managers. Each
woman has a distinct style (Ms. Yucha, for instance, admits
she's messy, while Ms. Queno is neat). But the pair, both
mothers of two children, have made it work. They aren't
supervisors, so there isn't the problem of subordinates
answering to two masters. They hash out differences privately
and stay in close touch by phone. Ms. Queno works the first
half of the week, Ms. Yucha the second, and they confer over
lunch on Wednesday.
   Their boss, Paul Rannenberg, acknowledges that he had
initial reservations -- but says he'd now welcome an entire
staff of job sharers. "The synergy you get can be great, and
if one is sick or on vacation, the other is always there."
   At what point is flexible scheduling more trouble than
it's worth? When employees try to take advantage of the
situation, says Ms. Herchenroether. One employee, she says,
arranged a flextime schedule when his parents became ill --
but instead of honoring the new arrangement arrived at work
later and later. Another wanted to work just 20 hours a month
-- not nearly enough to make a contribution.
   But if there's a will, there's usually a way. She recalls
the dilemma faced by a data processing manager when three of
her six staffers, all specialists, became pregnant at the
same time. All three wanted family leaves and part-time
schedules on their return. "The thought of having even one
out was frightening," says Ms. Herchenroether. But the
manager mapped out a plan to cross-train the employees to do
each other's jobs. She also found temporary workers to fill
in during family leaves.
   "The manager said she was bending over backwards to
accommodate everyone because she'd eventually want the same
treatment," says Ms. Herchenroether. And indeed, the manager
became pregnant nine months later and is currently on a
family leave.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0143
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0143.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Telecredit, Check-Guarantee Provider,
   Holds Merger Talks With Several Firms
   ----
   By Rhonda L. Rundle
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5B
</SO>
<CO>
   TCRD
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- Telecredit Inc., a provider of
check-guarantee and credit-card processing services, said
that it is holding talks with several companies about a
possible business combination.
   "Telecredit believes it is in the best interests of its
shareholders to explore the possibility of such a
transaction," said Lee A. Ault III, chairman and chief
executive officer.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Telecredit told shareholders last year that it was
considering various ways to use its excess cash, including a
stock buy-back, recapitalization or leveraged buy-out. After
"we were approached by some companies of substance, we
thought we might as well include {a merger} as one of the
alternatives, " Mr. Ault said Friday.
   The announcement propelled Telecredit shares up $9.375 to
$52.50 in national over-the-counter trading. Nearly 1.2
million shares changed hands, more than 25 times the stock's
average daily volume. The closing price gives Telecredit a
market value of about $578 million.
   Telecredit is best known for its check service used by
retailers and other merchants to verify customers' personal
checks. If a check bounces after Telecredit approves it,
Telecredit "purchases" the check from the retailer.
Dominating the market, Telecredit guarantees more than $7
billion of checks annually.
   Credit-card and debit card processing services, mainly for
MasterCard and Visa transactions, make up the other main part
of Telecredit's business. The company's customers are 1,700
credit unions and small and medium-sized financial
institutions that don't process their own credit-card
payments.
   Analysts suggested that Telecredit's suitors probably are
large financial institutions seeking to expand existing
services or add new ones. Most banks wouldn't be interested
because they wouldn't want to reduce their regulatory capital
by putting substantial goodwill on their books, the analysts
said.
   Mr. Ault wouldn't describe the suitors, but he said that
"the only {companies} that make sense would be those where
there is a strategic fit and they have some size to do it."
   The board hasn't set a deadline to review the options, but
the process "won't drag on for a long time," he said.
Telecredit has retained Dillon, Read &amp; Co. and Alex. Brown &amp;
Sons Inc. as financial advisers.
   Telecredit isn't widely followed by securities analysts,
possibly because its niche business doesn't neatly fall into
any large industry group. Joseph A. Stieven, an analyst at
Stifel, Nicolaus &amp; Co. in St. Louis, counseled clients Friday
to "take profits" because the stock "could drop as quickly as
it came up" if a transaction doesn't materialize.
   Mr. Stieven, who has followed Telecredit for four years,
praises management for achieving pretax profit margins of 27%
for the nine months ended Jan. 31. After more than 20 years
at the helm, Telecredit's 53-year-old chief executive, Mr.
Ault, "is highly energetic and has sharp people working for
him."
   One of Telecredit's attractions is that it throws off a
lot of cash. The company currently has about $82 million, or
$7 a share, in cash and no debt. While earnings growth has
slowed a bit in recent years, analysts are forecasting future
growth of about 13% to 15% a year.
   Telecredit was hurt in recent years by the disappointing
performance of a subsidiary that launched a computerized
system to prevent counterfeiting of stocks and bonds. The
unit, most of whose operations have been phased out,
accounted for $38 million in operating losses in fiscal years
1984 through 1988, one analyst calculated.
   In the year ended April 30, 1989, Telecredit posted net
income of $24.9 million, or $2.26 a share, on revenue of
$158.7 million. For the nine months ended Jan. 31, the
company had net income of $21.9 million, or $1.98 a share, on
revenue of $129.2 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
