<HL>
   Appeals Court Says
   Merrill Must Pay
   Punitive Damages
   ---
   Award in `Churning' Case
   Is Upheld Even Though
   Account's Value Rose 50%
   ----
   By Michael Siconolfi
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13
</SO>
<CO>
   MER
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Small investors can sometimes punish their
brokers in court even when they make big bucks.
   At least that's the message from the Eighth U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in St. Paul, Minn. In a 3-0 decision, the
court Friday upheld a $2 million punitive damage award
against Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. in an unusual excessive-trading
case involving the account of a deceased widow.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Merrill, the nation's largest securities firm, says it is
"greatly disappointed" with the decision, and may appeal. One
reason: The investor's account actually rose 50% during the
time of the complaint, Merrill Lynch says.
   It's rare that investors are awarded punitive damages when
they haven't suffered monetary losses, securities lawyers
say. "It's extraordinary," says Sam Scott Miller, a former
general counsel at PaineWebber Group Inc. and currently a
partner at Orrick, Herrington &amp; Sutcliffe in New York.
   Punitive damages are generally awarded to punish and deter
a defendant found to have acted recklessly or maliciously.
(Most cases involving punitive damages occur when investors'
nest eggs have been depleted.) Punitive damages are applied
in addition to awards intended to compensate for actual
injury or loss.
   The award for the estate of Ethlyn Davis, the investor,
also included $100,000 in compensatory damages. Merrill Lynch
said the $2.1 million total has been "previously reserved
for." A federal jury awarded the amount in Sioux Falls, S.D.,
in August 1988.
   In court papers, Mrs. Davis alleged that from February
1982 to August 1984 former Merrill Lynch broker Steven Ulrich
"churned" her account, which had an average balance of
$144,000, by making 141 trades totaling $2 million. Churning
is excessive trading in a customer's account by a broker
solely to generate commissions.
   Despite the heavy trading, Merrill says in court papers
that the account actually made a net profit of more than
$53,000. But the appellate panel, in a 42-page decision,
said: "The gravity of the wrong committed by Merrill Lynch is
not mitigated by the fact that the account was nevertheless
profitable."
   Mr. Ulrich was terminated in August 1984 after other
customers complained of unauthorized trading in their
accounts, a Merrill Lynch spokesman says. Mrs. Davis died in
November 1986 at age 91.
   Arlo Sommervold, a lawyer for Mrs. Davis's estate, says
Mr. Ulrich should have made much more for his client,
contending that stocks were rising for much of the time the
alleged excessive trading took place. He says punitive
damages were justified.
   "You can't rob a bank and then, if they catch you, just
give the money back and everyone's even," Mr. Sommervold
says. "She's entitled to all the money she should have
earned."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0120
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0120.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Seven Journalists
   File $330 Million
   Suit Against Atex
   ----
   By Wade Lambert
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5B
</SO>
<CO>
   EK
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Journalists from five newspapers and a news
service sued Eastman Kodak Co.'s Atex electronic-publishing
unit for $330 million, claiming that using the Atex computer
system at work caused them permanent injuries.
   The lawsuit, filed in federal court in Manhattan, alleged
that Atex knew the computer system could pose health risks,
such as injuries to the wrists and arms, from repetitive use.
The lawsuit accused the company of negligence in not
notifying users of the risks or changing the computer system,
which is used for reporting and editing.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The lawsuit said Atex "disregarded medical and scientific
information, studies, tests, data and literature concerning
the causal relationship between the repetitive use of
computer systems and cumulative trauma disorders," as the
ailments are known.
   A spokesman for Atex said the company hadn't seen the
suit. He said the company doesn't comment on issues that are
in litigation. Eastman Kodak, the parent company, isn't named
as a defendant.
   The plaintiffs are seven journalists working for both the
New York and Long Island editions of Newsday, Discount Store
News, the Village Voice, American Banker and the Associated
Press, and one former American Banker reporter. Three of the
plaintiffs' spouses also are plaintiffs, seeking additional
damages for the loss of the journalists' support.
   The journalists claim their injuries prevent them from
pursuing normal activities and employment. The injuries
include carpal tunnel syndrome, tendinitis and nerve
disorders, the lawsuit said.
   In the lawsuit, the journalists also alleged that the
computer system -- including the keyboard and video display
terminal -- was defectively designed. A similar suit was
filed against Atex in state court in Manhattan earlier this
month by three other Newsday reporters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
