<HL>
   Credit Ratings
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C5
</SO>
<CO>
   HFD REL
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<LP>
   HOMEFED Corp. (San Diego) -- Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. said
it lowered its ratings on $110 million of debt of HomeFed
Corp.'s HomeFed Bank unit, citing concerns about the thrift's
exposure to deteriorating real estate markets. The ratings
concern said it lowered its rating on HomeFed Bank's
subordinated debt to triple-B-minus from triple-B-plus. It
lowered its rating on the thrift's long-term certificates of
deposit to triple-B from single-A-minus. It affirmed at
single-A-2 its ratings on the bank's commercial paper and
short-term certificates of deposit. HomeFed officials
couldn't be reached for comment.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   PHILADELPHIA -- Citing a chronic fiscal imbalance,
Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. lowered its rating on $1.3 billion of
Philadelphia general obligation bonds to Triple-B-minus from
Triple-B-plus. The rating agency cited the city's inability
to erase its deficit, which is expected to reach $60 million
for the year ending June 30. It would be the city's third
consecutive deficit and next fiscal year's budget also has a
likelihood of an imbalance, S&amp;P said. Other issues downgraded
to Triple-B-minus from Triple-B-plus include $9 million
issued by the Philadelphia Redevelopment Authority, $6
million issued by the Philadelphia Parking Authority, and
$7.6 million issued by the Philadelphia Parking Authority. A
final rating is still pending on the March 1990 offering of
$148 million of variable rate general obligations, backed by
a letter of credit by Fuji Bank. S&amp;P said Philadelphia's
financial outlook for fiscal 1991 is not expected to improve.
A recent court stipulation will require the city to provide
an additional $32 million for child welfare. The city also
may be required by court order to refund an additional $25
million in real estate transfer tax collections that were
declared illegal a year ago. S&amp;P also anticipates the city
having to pay $20 million in labor arbitration settlements
and an indeterminate amount in court costs.
   ---
   RELIANCE GROUP HOLDINGS Inc. (New York) -- Standard &amp;
Poor's Corp. said it raised its ratings on this insurance and
financial holding company's senior debt to double-B from
single-B-plus and on subordinated debt to single-B-plus from
single-B-minus. The rating concern affirmed its ratings on
debt of related entities, including Reliance Group Inc.,
Reliance Financial Services Corp., and Reliance Insurance Co.
About $1.2 billion in debt was affected. S&amp;P noted that
Reliance Group Holdings continues to show improved financial
leverage, augmented by a large capital gain from the sale of
an insurance unit in April, and that it expects the trend of
improved financial leverage to continue. But S&amp;P lowered to
triple-B-plus from single-A its rating on the claims-paying
ability of United Pacific Life Insurance Co., which S&amp;P said
has a "significant tolerance for single-issue concentrations
in its large high-yield portfolio."
</TEXT>
