<HL>
   A Libertarian Governor?
   ----
   By Tim W. Ferguson
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<IN>
BIOGRAPHY (BIO)
</IN>
<LP>
   PHOENIX -- Amid the piles on Sam Steiger's desk is a
political guidebook entitled "Break the Rules and Win." It
was someone's fitting gift to an Arizona institution who is
like no other candidate for a governorship this fall.
   The Republican rancher-businessman is a candidate without
a car phone, holding his pipe instead as he shuttles
contentedly about this metropolis in a Dodge convertible. He
sometimes sounds like he's running to prove a point to the
campaign consultants of America. He emphasizes a distaste for
"packaging." His radio spots were cut from a Steiger
monologue his sons taped in their father's kitchen in
Prescott. No pollster pointed him toward winning issues, and
the ads run randomly without an attempt to target subject
matter to station audience.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the jumble of politics in the nation's
second-fastest-growing state (behind only Nevada), maybe it
pays just to let the rhetorical missiles fall where they
will. Arizona is an uneasy mix of cowboys &amp; Indians, retirees
and urban professionals, but the fact that nearly a million
of them found their way here in the 1980s gives it added
national weight. It should gain two congressional districts
from the new Census, and that makes the governorship a bigger
prize. Moreover, Mr. Steiger's beliefs, a modified form of
laissez faire, have special significance here, where the
political drift is toward the bigger government that typifies
populous jurisdictions.
   Long removed from his native Brooklyn, Mr. Steiger appears
comfortable with who he is, where's he been and what he
thinks. That's not as clear a plus as it might seem, because
in standard political terms, he is damaged goods.
   His story began auspiciously enough, with election to the
Arizona Senate in 1960 at age 31. He was a congressman at 37
and recognized as a conservative comer during the Nixon
presidency. After five House terms, however, his bid for the
U.S. Senate in 1976 was entangled in a bitter primary that he
says included anti-Semitism by his opponent; he was defeated
in the fall by Democrat Dennis DeConcini.
   Thus began a decade of setbacks private and public. The
cattle business went sour. In 1982 he ran for governor -- as
the nominee of the Libertarian Party. Mr. Steiger got an
unusually high 5% of the vote then, but the link with what
even he and many other small-L libertarians regard as a
fringe group did not enhance his gravitas. The Purple Heart
winner in Korea was already an oddball in some eyes because
of a brush with the law years before when he shot some feral
burros in the behind. (The incident still comes up.)
   Mr. Steiger re-entered public life as an aide to Evan
Mecham, the right-wing populist elected governor in a
three-way race in 1986. He left his post prior to Mr.
Mecham's impeachment and removal by the Legislature in 1988,
but not before he himself was caught up in the
political/legal storm. He was convicted of extortion for
threatening a parole official's job, but an appellate court,
apparently accepting Mr. Steiger's contention that his
characteristic bluster was distorted by an anti-Mecham
prosecutor, overturned the verdict.
   In his campaign appearances Mr. Steiger jokes about his
hard times. He portrays himself as an "SOB" who can whip a
fractious Legislature into action, and as a man whose own ups
and downs suit him for governing a state that's suffered a
real-estate finance blowout in recent years but, according to
Mr. Steiger, is primed for recovery.
   Mr. Mecham, also trying a comeback as one of Mr. Steiger's
opponents in the Sept. 11 Republican primary, includes his
former aide in his stump vitriol. The pair are among the
three leading GOP contenders. (Fife Symington, a wealthy
developer, is considered the front-runner by some.)
   Mr. Steiger has been less harsh on his former boss, though
he points up management and personal weaknesses. What brought
the two together in 1986 was a shared antipathy for Arizona's
power structure, which these days is a bedfellowship of
statist Democrats and corporatist Republicans. Mr. Steiger
says he wanted to strike at the expanding governmental mass
through streamlinings and privatizations, but Mr. Mecham was
distracted by uproars over his crankiness toward cosmopolitan
culture. With only a limited political base to begin with,
Mr. Mecham couldn't withstand a press frenzy fed by his own
maladroitness. He was later acquitted of criminal charges.
   The Democrat who took his place, longtime Secretary of
State Rose Mofford, generally restored the policies of Mr.
Mecham's predecessor, Bruce Babbitt. Symbolically foremost
among these: a paid holiday to honor Martin Luther King Jr.
After a petition campaign made the first attempt at
reinstituting the King day off subject to a referendum this
November, Ms. Mofford and a media-led coalition got the
legislators this spring to pass a bill to circumvent the
vote. This has led to another active petition drive to get
the issue back on the November ballot. Mr. Mecham's people
are leading the effort. Meanwhile, a referendum drive is
pledged by opponents of a tax increase that may pass in the
legislature today to accommodate rapid growth in state
spending.
   The particular volatility of Arizona politics in 1990 is
an environment the rough-and-tumble Mr. Steiger may find
advantageous. He says, however, that stability is required
because "Arizona is fast earning a national reputation as the
Venice Beach of the world" because of its freakish politics,
and that his free-market pragmatism and common sense are the
antidote.
   Indeed, Mr. Steiger appears to have kept at least a foot
in the establishment's camp. His campaign treasurer is a top
official of the Phoenix 40, a civic group that functions as a
sort of executive council of what might be called the
governing Arizocracy. And he has taken a progressive stance
on some social issues. He backs the King holiday. He urges
more use of "intensive probation" as an alternative to prison
time, which he says breeds more crime. And he favors abortion
rights, admitting he's lost conservative backers as a result
but arguing that a lucrative black market would spring up in
the event of restrictions.
   Although he has discarded the formal affiliation, Mr.
Steiger remains essentially a libertarian. He says economists
Milton Friedman and Murray Rothbard have most influenced him.
When asked, he's prone to say that farmers shouldn't get
subsidized water and other businesses shouldn't be favored
either, except possibly on land-improvement costs. But his
platform comes off as rather moderate. He dodges the
drug-legalization issue. Privatization remains his way of
slimming down the state agencies, 40% of whose employees, he
says, are in management.
   A big issue for Mr. Steiger recently has been the rapid
growth of the state university system. (Arizona State now has
65,000 students; the University of Arizona, 40,000.) He
suggests that many enrollees belong instead in a beefed up
community-college system.
   Mr. Steiger likes to bash the bar. One of his aims is to
have "lawyers leaving Arizona for lack of business, and
business coming for lack of lawyers." He seeks to require
losing plaintiffs to pay civil-court costs of the defense in
order to deter litigiousness. It was reported last week
however, that Mr. Steiger himself hasn't paid a 1984 judgment
and costs from a civil case he initiated.
   Although he lists as qualifications a penchant for
personal deal-making and "a perverse delight in making people
mad," two traits that might be ascribed to Evan Mecham, Mr.
Steiger hastens to draw a contrast. He knows when to cajole,
he says, and would delegate authority, whereas Mr. Mecham
wouldn't. He recalls being in the governor's office during
one of the tense periods when Mr. Mecham, an auto dealer in
private life, was interrupted to approve an advertising
jingle his son, then running the dealership, had conceived.
   Mr. Steiger may be an effective bargainer in the halls of
power, and he's uncommonly funny for a politico, but his
people skills on the campaign trail are being tested. Like
many successful and/or wealthy men, he can seem oblivious to
indignities felt by those below his station, his gruff humor
only making matters worse. At a small Kiwanis luncheon in
May, Mr. Steiger joked a couple of times about the uninspired
Red Lobster venue. This was received well enough, but then he
tried a variant of the "food's not so good, but the service
is lousy" line in front of the waiter. The youth wore one of
the chain's "Star Performer" pins, and despite an "only
kidding" assurance, the candidate didn't leave 'em laughing
at that one.
   Nevertheless, for much of the electorate, a contrast
between Mr. Steiger and the likely Democratic nominee, the
recently resigned mayor of Phoenix, Terry Goddard, could work
in the GOP's favor. Mr. Goddard, himself the son of a former
Arizona governor, is perceived as a yuppie. Before that
match-up can occur, though, Mr. Steiger must turn back Mr.
Mecham, who retains a loyal following, and Mr. Symington, the
pick of the corporate elite.
   Polls show the three Republicans in a tight race, but Mr.
Steiger isn't listening to any numbers anyway. He's only
speaking his mind. Just don't expect to hear from him while
he's driving.
   ---
   Mr. Ferguson is a Journal columnist and a member of its
editorial board.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0091
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0091.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Energy Agency to Begin
   Talks With TRW Unit
   On $1 Billion Contract
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TRW
</CO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
ENERGY DEPARTMENT (ERG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Energy Department announced it will
comply with a federal court order and begin negotiations with
a TRW Inc. subsidiary on a possible award of a 10-year, $1
billion contract.
   TRW Environmental Safety Systems Inc. lost out in initial
bidding for the contract to a consortium led by Bechtel
Systems Management Inc., a subsidiary of Bechtel Group. But
TRW went to court and won a federal claims court order last
August barring award of the contract, as it was originally
solicited, to anyone but TRW.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department had been planning to appeal the
ruling. However, it announced Friday it is changing course to
try to prevent further delays in work on its high-level
nuclear-waste disposal program. The department said it will
drop its appeal "if a mutually satisfactory contractual
agreement can be achieved" with TRW.
   Although TRW wasn't the agency's first choice, it called
the company "a qualified contractor capable of successfully
performing the work." The contract is for systems
engineering, development and management services for the
government's waste program. The department currently is
evaluating a Yucca Mountain, Nev., site for possible use as
the first permanent dump for highly radioactive waste from
nuclear power plants.
   The department said the Bechtel-led consortium was barred
from receiving the contract "through no fault of its own."
TRW had alleged in claims court that the selection process
was illegal and that the department used different criteria
than it had said it would when it selected Bechtel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0090
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0090.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   Mexican Telephone Group
   Approves Recapitalization
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   TFONY LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   MEXICO CITY -- Shareholders of Telefonos de Mexico
approved a recapitalization plan that should pave the way for
the state-controlled Mexican telephone monopoly's
privatization.
   The recapitalization, which includes a stock dividend of
new, limited-voting shares, is designed to reduce the size of
the investment a buyer will need to obtain operating control
of the company, Mexican officials said. Under the plan,
full-voting shares will be reduced to just 40% of the total
shares oustanding; the buyer will need to obtain the majority
of only the full-voting shares to gain operating control. The
government currently holds an interest of slightly more than
50% in Telmex.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The new capital structure was approved by 87% of
shareholders at a special meeting Friday afternoon. In New
York, amid investor nervousness over the plan, Telmex's
American depositary receipts were the most actively traded
stock on the Nasdaq, closing at $1.53 bid, down 18 cents.
Under the plan, Telmex will use $230 million in accumulated
earnings to issue a dividend of 1.5 shares of new Class L
stock for each share held. The Class L shares will have
limited voting rights.
   Of the 40% of shares outstanding with full voting rights,
slightly more than half will be held by the government. A
group seeking operating control of Telmex would have to pay
roughly $1.5 billion for the government's full voting shares,
based on recent market prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0089
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0089.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Investors in Britain Raise an Eyebrow
   To Big Board's Nighttime Trading Plan
   ----
   By Richard E. Rustin
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Among British investors being wooed by the New
York Stock Exchange with its plan to trade stocks in the wee
hours, reaction runs the gamut from lukewarm acceptance to
icy opposition.
   Some big investors doubt there will be enough heavy
hitters to provide smooth trading during the graveyard shift.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Under the plan, continuous trading in Big Board issues
would be conducted by computer after the exchange closes at 4
p.m. Eastern time, which is 9 p.m. London time. The Big Board
said it would begin such trading this year, but hasn't
specified dates. Starting in 1991, it also would let brokers
enter potential trades all night, with computers matching and
executing orders at 8 p.m. (1 a.m. in London), midnight (5
a.m.) and 5 a.m. (10 a.m.).
   The plan is designed partly to woo business from London's
International Stock Exchange, where the Seaq International
system trades 49 Big Board issues. The London system recently
has amassed a healthy, but far from enormous, chunk of volume
in Big Board stocks, mostly when the New York market was
closed. Between last February, when London began keeping such
statistics, and the end of May, Seaq International volume in
those stocks totaled 816 million shares -- about one good
week of volume in New York.
   The London exchange said Friday that it hadn't any plans
to expand trading hours in response to the Big Board's move.
The London market is open from 8:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m., but
Seaq International trades can take place at any time. Few
dealers linger after the close, however.
   Investors are concerned about inadequate service in an
after-hours market. "I'm skeptical about how much liquidity
would be provided," Graeme Johnson, a fund manager for
Glasgow-based Scottish Amicable Investment Managers, said.
"Trading should be fairly thin. That would mean wide spreads
and greater volatility. We would reserve judgment as to
whether we'd trade."
   Moreover, the Big Board plan seems to overlook the
long-view approach many British investors take. Baillie
Gifford &amp; Co., an Edinburgh-based fund manager, said this is
why it isn't interested in the Big Board's plan. Gavin J.N.
Gemmell, chief pension investments manager, said: "We try to
buy stocks in successful companies and hold them for a long
period. We don't care if we pay an extra eighth {of a point,
or 12.5 cents, for a share}. If we've made the basic decision
right, we're going to make a lot of money, anyway. If you've
got that basic attitude, it doesn't make much sense to come
into the office in the middle of the night."
   Even some who cautiously endorsed the idea predicated this
on the after-hours market's attracting enough trading volume
to minimize wild price swings. But they acknowledged that
their reticence could lessen the new market's chances of
success. "We're cautiously positive. The move is a good one,"
Ian Young, U.S. investment manager for Norwich Union
Insurance Group, said. "If the liquidity is there, we're
prepared to use it."
   Some investors, while generally opposed to the plan, said
after-hours trading could be a useful tool in emergencies,
such as the October market plunges of 1987 and 1989. "We
certainly wouldn't trade after hours as a matter of course,
but we probably would do it in exceptional circumstances when
quite a lot of dealing has to be done," said Richard A.
Barfield, chief investment manager for Edinburgh-based
Standard Life Assurance Co.
   Some London units of Big Board member firms, eager for
more business in a market long bereft of heavy volume,
welcomed the plan. "It must help us. These are serious moves"
by the Big Board, Bernie Leaver, head of equity trading at
Shearson Lehman Hutton International Inc., said. "If that's
the way of the world, we're ready for it."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
