<HL>
   International:
   Anglo American Says Units
   To Trim Mining Operations
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   ANGLY FSCNY VAALY
</CO>
<IN>
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
</IN>
<LP>
   JOHANNESBURG -- Anglo American Corp. of South Africa said
it will curtail mining operations at two of its subsidiaries
because of the plummeting price of gold.
   Anglo American said the moves at its Free State
Consolidated Gold Mines Ltd. and Vaal Reefs Exploration &amp;
Mining Co. subsidiaries would cut at least 7,800 jobs.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The price of gold reached a four-year low of $346.25 an
ounce in New York and London last Thursday before recovering
amid central bank buying. Gold is South Africa's major
industry, earning more than half the country's foreign
currency.
   Lionel Hewitt, managing director of Anglo American's gold
and uranium division, said the curtailment of operations will
take place over the next nine months. He said the cutbacks at
Vaal Reefs won't necessarily eliminate jobs, because workers
may be assigned to other areas of the mine.
   Operating reductions at Free State will reduce its gold
output by less than 1%, while the proposed action at Vaal
Reefs probably will improve production, Mr. Hewitt said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0076
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0076.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Do We Want
   U.S. to Be Rich
   Or Japan Poor?
   ----
   By Robert Reich
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Which of these futures do you prefer?
   (a) Between now and 2000, the American economy grows a
respectable 25%, but the Japanese economy grows a whopping
75%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   (b) Between now and 2000, the American economy grows only
10%, and the Japanese economy grows an anemic 10.3%.
   If you chose (b), you're in good company. I've posed the
same choice to several groups of people in recent months -- a
class of Harvard graduate students, a conference of
executives of large American corporations, a conference of
Wall Street investment bankers, a gathering of senior State
Department bureaucrats, a meeting of several hundred citizens
of Belmont, Mass., and a gathering of professional
economists. A majority of every group except the last voted
for (b). The economists all voted for (a).
   Why would so many people prefer (b)? The economists had a
hard time believing that thoughtful Americans willingly would
choose to sacrifice a gain in wealth of 15 percentage points.
The answer, I think, is that the non-economists looked at
relative gains. They don't want the Japanese to catch up with
us and then move ahead. The specter of an economic goliath
towering over the U.S. from across the Pacific frightens them
to the core.
   ---
   This is the dark side of America's relationship with Japan
that never gets talked about, but colors everything else.
Forget the trade imbalances, the negotiations over whether
they'll buy our baseball bats or allow Boone Pickens to buy
their companies, the interminable "structural impediments
initiatives" and summit meetings, the righteous American
indignation over Japanese "dumping" and unfair subsidies to
Japanese companies. We say that all we want is a "level
playing field," but that's not quite true. We also want our
team to remain bigger and stronger than theirs.
   Japan could agree to every one of our demands to buy more
American goods and invite in more American investors, and yet
the (b) problem would remain and probably get worse. The
Japanese economy is growing fast not because Japan keeps us
out but because the Japanese are investing like mad and
working like hell. America is growing slowly because
Americans are doing neither.
   Americans who choose (b) won't be satisfied until the
widening gap in the growth rates of Japan and the U.S. begins
to close and America regains the lead. But for this to happen
we would have to radically step up our investment in
factories, machinery, research, education, training, roads,
ports and everything else that would equip us to produce
more. And we'd have to work harder, longer and better. The
Japanese, on the other hand, would have to learn to live it
up -- stop investing as much and be less diligent on the job.
   ---
   If all this seems unlikely to happen, there's another,
more insidious, remedy the (b) choosers might ultimately
pursue. Disconnect the trade and investment lines between the
two nations -- lines that have fueled our growth and fueled
theirs even faster: Block Japanese imports, bar Japanese
investments, prevent the Japanese from acquiring U.S.
technologies. Both nations would lose -- but the Japanese
would lose more. America would sacrifice the gains of (a) to
prevent Japan from enjoying the much larger gains of (a).
   It has not yet come to this, but it may. American
anxieties temporarily subside each time the Japanese
cautiously accede to U.S. demands to open their market and
buy more American goods, as in the most recent accord. But in
a few months, when Americans once again ponder Japan's
growing economic might, the anxieties may come back even
larger than before.
   Are the (b) choosers irrational and irresponsible? Or are
they wisely responding to the "Realpolitik" of global power,
and the lessons of world history? I'm enough of an economist
to think it must be the former, but not so much of one that I
don't have a lingering doubt. I do know that unless we
confront the (b) crowd's fears openly and directly, our
long-term relationship with Japan will continue to
deteriorate -- regardless of how many American baseball bats,
modems, Toys `R' Us franchises, and Boone Pickenses they
allow in.
   ---
   Mr. Reich teaches political economy at Harvard's Kennedy
School of Government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0075
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0075.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Law:
   Siegel's Cooperation With U.S. Results
   In Lenient Sentence for Securities Fraud
   ----
   By Laurie P. Cohen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- In a move that reflects the extraordinary
value that courts and prosecutors place on cooperation by
defendants in securities fraud cases, former Wall Street
investment banker Martin A. Siegel was sentenced to two
months in prison for his crimes.
   In imposing the lenient sentence, U.S. District Judge
Robert J. Ward said that the two securities fraud-related
felony counts to which Mr. Siegel pleaded guilty in February
1987 were "serious." But Judge Ward added that Mr. Siegel's
"cooperation, his contrition and his candor under difficult
circumstances" prompted him to order a much lighter sentence
than many had expected. Mr. Siegel could have been sentenced
to as long as 10 years in prison.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Judge Ward also noted that the government's position, put
forth in a sentencing memo released on Friday, was "not
typical." The government, in its memo and in court, praised
Mr. Siegel as a "credible and reliable" witness who
cooperated despite "an intense campaign of villification."
The government said the assistance of the 42-year-old Mr.
Siegel enabled prosecutors to learn about wrongdoing they
would not otherwise have uncovered.
   The sentencing of Mr. Siegel, Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co.'s
former chief takeover strategist, ended a saga that began on
Nov. 14, 1986, when a federal marshal thrust a subpoena into
Mr. Siegel's hands relating to his dealings with Ivan F.
Boesky, the convicted former stock speculator. Mr. Boesky's
cooperation, which began the insider trading investigation,
led the government to Mr. Siegel.
   Mr. Siegel began cooperating with the government and
eventually pleaded guilty to exchanging insider information
with Mr. Boesky and with Robert M. Freeman, the former head
of arbitrage at Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. Mr. Siegel also paid
more than $9 million in fines.
   Mr. Siegel's cooperation proved a bonanza for the
government. The Kidder unit agreed in June 1987 to pay $25.3
million to settle Securities and Exchange Commission charges
in connection with Mr. Siegel's actions. The government also
disclosed for the first time in its sentencing memo that
leads provided by Mr. Siegel resulted in the conviction last
year of five officials of Princeton/Newport Partners and a
former Drexel trader on racketeering and other charges.
   Mr. Freeman pleaded guilty last August to one felony
count. Mr. Freeman, who had long denied that he had done
anything wrong, admitted to using inside information received
from Mr. Siegel in connection with the proposed takeover of
Beatrice Cos. by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. In April, Mr.
Freeman was sentenced to four months in jail.
   The government has said the crime to which Mr. Freeman
pleaded guilty was one of many he committed. But until
Friday, the government hadn't elaborated on Mr. Freeman's
other alleged misdeeds. In its memo, the government said that
beginning in 1984, Messrs. Freeman and Siegel passed inside
information to each other about companies involved in "at
least twelve takeover situations."
   The government also said that Mr. Siegel provided credible
information about a 1985 telephone call in which Mr. Siegel
received a tip from Mr. Freeman about Unocal Corp. Mr. Siegel
then ordered Kidder traders to buy securities based on that
tip. The government said in the memo that it also seized a
tape from Princeton/Newport on which Mr. Freeman is heard
giving that defunct firm similar information about Unocal.
   On Friday, Mr. Freeman's attorneys continued to deny that
he had engaged in further wrongdoing. "Mr. Freeman has taken
and passed a lie detector test on his statements that no
illicit arrangement with Siegel ever existed and that he
never deliberately gave Siegel confidential information to
help Siegel make a trading decision," the attorneys, Paul
Curran and Robert Fiske Jr., said in a statement.
   According to individuals familiar with the drafting of the
government's memo, Messrs. Curran and Fiske successfully
sought to block the government from including more details
about Mr. Freeman's actions. Those details were included in a
probation report that was not made public. Mr. Curran
declined to comment.
   Mr. Siegel had accepted $700,000 in cash payments from Mr.
Boesky in 1983 and 1984 in exchange for information he
provided to Mr. Boesky. Judge Ward noted that the profits of
Mr. Boesky, who recently completed a three-year prison term,
totaled $30 million.
   "After Mr. Boesky received a three-year sentence {in
1987}, I began to think about Mr. Siegel," Judge Ward said.
"At that time, I was of the view that" a prison term of "18
months to two years would be reasonable" for Mr. Siegel.
   Judge Ward said that in the "intervening period, I was
advised that the government wished to defer Mr. Siegel's
sentence because of his cooperation." Largely because of that
cooperation, Judge Ward decided that Mr. Siegel should serve
"a sentence less than imposed on Mr. Freeman," who has
refused to cooperate with the government.
   Legal experts say that Judge Ward is likely to be attacked
for the lenient sentence. Jed Rakoff, an attorney for Mr.
Siegel, said: "The sentence was fair and just and reflected
very well on the degree to which Judge Ward immersed himself
in the particulars of the case."
   Mr. Siegel was also sentenced to five years probation and
ordered to perform 1,500 hours of community service in
Jacksonville, Fla., near his home. He is to begin serving the
sentence on July 16.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
