<HL>
   Ford, Breaking With Recent Practice,
   Unveils Broad Midyear Price Increases
   ----
   By Jacqueline Mitchell
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   F
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   Ford Motor Co., for the first time in three years,
announced broad, midyear price increases ranging from $58 to
$134 on many of its cars and trucks.
   The move is unusual because U.S. auto makers have
generally avoided midyear, base-price increases for the past
few years. Also, the U.S. auto market has been relatively
soft since February. Sales of Ford's cars and trucks fell 14%
in May from a year-earlier levels.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But the No. 2 auto maker needed to raise base prices on
most 1990 models and one 1991 model "to partially offset
increases in ongoing operating costs and product-related
costs," Robert L. Rewey, vice president-North American sales
operations, said in a statement.
   In March, Ford raised option prices by an average of $29.
A month later, General Motors Corp. also boosted option
prices. Neither GM nor Chrysler Corp. have announced any
broad vehicle base-price increases, however. Ford said it
didn't change option prices in its latest action.
   The increase in base prices for cars, which took effect
Friday, averages $49, or three-tenths of one percent. The
boost in truck prices averages $95, or six-tenths of one
percent. Ford didn't cut prices on any models, a spokesman
said.
   The largest increase came on the new 1991 Ford Explorer
sport utility vehicle, which was introduced only last March
with a base price of $19,015. Ford raised Explorer's base
price 0.7% or $134 to $19,149.
   Explorer has sold well since March, but another new Ford
product, the redesigned Escort subcompact, hasn't. Combined
sales of the new Escort and the model it replaces were off
17.2% in May; Ford didn't change price on either version.
Base prices for the Mercury Tracer, introduced June 14, and
the Mercury Capri, due out in July, were also unchanged. "We
felt it wasn't necessary" with the newer models, the Ford
spokesman said.
   Ford also didn't raise prices on other, less-popular
products including 1990 Ford Ranger compact pickup truck, the
1990 Ford Probe sporty car and the Festiva subcompact. "Those
vehicles aren't selling as well," the Ford spokesman said. A
price hike could further dampen sales that already "need
stimulation."
   The biggest price jump on passenger cars came on Ford's
top three luxury models. The base prices of the 1990 Lincoln
Town Car, Continental and Mark VII all rose by $122. The new
price for the Town Car is $28,110; for the Continental,
$29,546; and for the Mark VII, $29,369.
   Sales of the Town Car during the first five months of the
year have been stronger than the Continental and Mark VII,
showing a 39.1% increase during the period.
   The smallest price increase, $58, came on the two-door
Ford Tempo GL, now $9,541, the Mustang LX sedan, $9,514; and
the two-door Topaz GS, $10,065.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0011
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0011.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Pickens Poised Again to Battle Koito
   But Sees Little Chance of Early Gains
   ----
   By Kathryn Graven
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   J.KOI MLP TOYOY NSANY MC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Proclaiming himself wiser in the ways of Japanese
business, Texas oilman and corporate raider T. Boone Pickens
Jr. comes to Japan this week for another round of battle with
Koito Manufacturing Co.
   But analysts, and even Mr. Pickens himself, don't expect
this visit to produce any breakthroughs in his campaign to
gain a voice in the auto-parts company's operations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As the largest shareholder, Mr. Pickens has been fighting
for more than a year for seats on Koito's board as well as
access to the company's financial records and pricing
policies. Through Amarillo, Texas-based Boone Co., a merchant
bank he controls, Mr. Pickens owns a 26% stake in Koito.
   "Sure, I've learned a lot in a year's time," Mr. Pickens
said in a telephone interview. "But I don't have any hope
that Koito will change its mind."
   Nevertheless, Mr. Pickens is determined to make his
presence felt at Koito's annual shareholders' meeting June
28. He is paying the airfare for 50 other Americans who own
Koito shares so they can attend the session in Tokyo with
him. And in a sugary appeal for support, he mailed videotapes
to around 4,000 Koito holders. In the video, which cost about
$20,000 to produce, Mr. Pickens outlines his proposals --
which include representation on the board, increased dividend
payments and an anti-greenmail resolution -- as he rides
horseback across the Texas range.
   "I've done everything I can to make it clear I am a
long-term investor," insists Mr. Pickens.
   But Koito is hardly preparing a red-carpet welcome. The
company argues that Mr. Pickens is really a greenmailer --
someone who tries to force a company to buy back his shares
at a premium. Mr. Pickens is welcome to attend the annual
meeting -- the company will even provide simultaneous
interpretation for the visiting Americans -- but that's as
far as the hospitality may go. "All of his proposals will be
denied," a Koito spokesman says.
   Koito's top brass aren't the only ones skeptical of Mr.
Pickens's intentions. Last week, Koito's labor union adopted
a resolution urging management to reject Mr. Pickens's
proposals. Sources say Japanese banks also are under pressure
to refrain from lending money to Mr. Pickens or any companies
associated with him.
   Mr. Pickens confirmed reports that a U.S. subsidiary of a
major Japanese bank had withdrawn its intent to join a group
of banks that backs Mesa Limited Partners Oil &amp; Gas Co., a
publicly held company that Mr. Pickens heads.
   Other major shareholders such as Toyota Motor Corp.,
Nissan Motor Co. and Matsushita Electric Industrial Co.
appear to have no time or sympathy for Mr. Pickens. "We
contacted all the large shareholders and said we'd like to
call on them. They have all said they will be out of town,"
says Mr. Pickens.
   While Koito and its supporters may be turning a deaf ear
to Mr. Pickens's complaints, Mr. Pickens has found more eager
listeners back in the U.S. Tapping into growing U.S.
resentment of Japanese business practices, Mr. Pickens has
emerged as a spokesman for those frustrated by Japan's
closely connected corporate relationships and has taken his
case to Washington to testify before congressional
committees.
   Analysts in Tokyo agree that Koito and Mr. Pickens seem
headed for a long, drawn-out fight. Mr. Pickens is suing
Koito in Tokyo District Court for access to its accounting
books and other records. He says Koito's pricing policies
favor Toyota -- its second largest holder, with a 19% stake
-- to the detriment of other holders. The next hearing is set
for July 12.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0010
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0010.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Amoco Will Post
   2nd-Quarter Gain
   On Iran Payment
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5A
</SO>
<CO>
   AN MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)
</GV>
<LP>
   CHICAGO -- Amoco Corp. said the settlement for about $600
million of all claims and counterclaims between it and Iran
will result in an undetermined second-quarter gain.
   The company said it expects to receive by the end of June
a net payment of about $594 million but that the gain will be
offset by income taxes and a charge that will also be booked
in the second quarter. The amount of the charge is
undetermined, in line with the completion of a study under
which the company has targeted specific worksites for
environmental cleanup.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the year-earlier quarter, the energy concern had net
income of $497 million, or 96 cents a share, on revenue of
$6.76 billion.
   The settlement ends Amoco's claims for compensation for
the seizure by Iran of its two major Iranian operations in
1978 and 1979. In Washington, U.S. officials said the
settlement wouldn't have any direct bearing on the chances of
gaining release of the six U.S. hostages still held by
pro-Iranian groups in Lebanon. "It's really not related,"
said a senior State Department official, pointing out that
Iran will be paying money, not receiving it.
   Nevertheless, the Bush administration privately hopes that
such progress at The Hague, and the promise of more, will
help induce economically strapped Iran to prod the Lebanese
kidnappers into fresh releases. President Bush has adopted a
policy of making whatever gestures appear reasonable in their
own right -- such as working to clear up claims -- and hoping
Tehran interprets them as favorable gestures.
   However, claims settlements so far seem to have had little
impact on the hostage problem. After a series of claims
settlements last month, no hostages were released, and Iran's
line even seemed to harden. Tehran and its allies are
demanding the release of Shiite prisoners from Israel and
Kuwait before any more hostages are released, and anti-U.S.
feelings have been rising in the Middle East lately as the
war of words against Israel has heated up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
