<HL>
   International --
   Japan Considers the Once Unthinkable:
   Easing 48-Year-Old Ban on Rice Imports
   ----
   By Jacob M. Schlesinger
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Support is growing in Japan for what was once
unthinkable but now may be inevitable: importing rice.
   The first signs of what will likely be a slow, steady
public campaign to accept an end to this nation's 48-year
virtual ban on foreign rice came June 8 when Komeito, an
opposition party often allied with the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party, said it would consider supporting partial
liberalization of rice trade. On June 13, Noboru Takeshita, a
former prime minister who remains a leading LDP power broker,
publicly praised the move as "courageous" and said public
opinion might shift in that direction.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Recent polls have shown strong majorities of the general
public backing such a move, reversing the results of similar
surveys from two years ago.
   Top elected officials have yet to openly embrace rice
imports and most still vehemently oppose it. Last week, five
LDP Diet members flew to Washington to try and persuade the
U.S. to drop its demand. Indeed, the positive but
noncommittal stirrings also come at a time when Japan is
trying to navigate through another set of difficult trade
negotiations with the U.S., the Structural Impediments
Initiative talks slated to end by early next month. But in a
nation where shifts in government policy are often carefully
choreographed to create the necessary public opinion, some
Japanese and American officials say a change is underway.
"People living in urban areas cannot understand why we give
subsidies to the farmers who produce rice," said a government
official who supports liberalization. "We should educate
Japanese public opinion to get back to normalcy" in accepting
such a move. He said a "campaign" would start with "political
leaders," and "when the time is right, then we {government
leaders} can come out." He added that "perhaps Mr.
Takeshita's remarks" were the beginning of the drive.
   An American Embassy official asserted Friday: "The
decision's been made for quite some time. The Japanese
understand that they're big players in the world trade
environment and they're in an untenable position in insisting
on a total import embargo."
   The Japanese government's official policy, submitted in
the ongoing multilateral Uruguay Round of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, says that a country should be
allowed "adjustment measures necessary to maintain its
required domestic production level in basic foodstuffs for
food security considerations." Both the Japanese and American
government officials interviewed said the statement doesn't
necessarily mean support for a continued import ban.
   The U.S. is asking Japan to loosen its rice policy as part
of the Uruguay Round, scheduled for completion by the end of
the year. The U.S. is also pressuring Europe to relax
agricultural trade restrictions, and is offering to do the
same if the other countries comply.
   Any change in Japan's policy would likely be symbolic,
however, at least at the beginning. Under the U.S. proposal,
countries would first convert agricultural quotas to tariffs,
then phase them out. According to U.S. calculations, Japan's
rice ban is the equivalent of a 700% tariff. If the ban were
replaced with that high a tariff, little rice would be
imported.
   Under outside pressure, Japan has over the past decade
taken down many of its formal trade restrictions. But the
U.S., recognizing the political sensitivity, had refrained
until the current GATT talks from pushing on rice, even as it
pried open Japan's beef and citrus markets two years ago. At
that time, the Diet endorsed a resolution, backed by all the
major parties, supporting the no-import rice policy.
   Japan has justified the protection of its rice farmers as
preserving cherished symbols of its agrarian heritage, and as
maintaining a policy of "food security" for a nation with new
natural resources. Consumers groups, especially housewives
organizations, have campaigned against rice imports, even
though it means higher prices. They also argue that foreign
rice is unsafe.
   (Actually, Japan does allow some importation of rice for
certain rice-based products, like rice crackers. Once,
according to one government official, Japan "borrowed" rice
from Korea during a shortage, then "paid it back" during a
surplus period.)
   But the reality is that the number of rice farmers is
dropping drastically, and many who remain do so simply for
tax breaks and government subsidies while holding other
full-time jobs. In the fiscal year ended March 31, per capita
rice consumption dropped 1.6%, the fourth consecutive annual
decline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0005
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0005.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Integrated Pact
   To Sell Interests
   Faces Hurdles
   ----
   By Robin Goldwyn Blumenthal
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   IRE AIMBZ AIMAZ CMM
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Integrated Resources Inc. agreed to sell its
general partner interests in its American Insured Mortgage
Investors series of limited partnerships to Krupp Cos. for
$38.6 million.
   But it isn't clear whether the agreement will be
completed. CRI Inc. is seeking to gain control of the
interests by approaching the partnership investors directly.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Integrated's agreement with Krupp was reached through an
auction supervised by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court here.
Integrated has been in bankruptcy proceedings since February,
and has been seeking to raise cash by selling assets. Krupp
is a Boston real estate investment manager.
   The agreement with Krupp, however, is conditioned on a
proposal by CRI being ended. A real estate investment trust
managed by CRI, a real estate syndicator based in Rockville,
Md., last week filed a proposal with the Securities and
Exchange Commission to offer to swap interests in two of its
real estate ventures for the Integrated partnership
interests. CRI values its proposed offer at about $664
million. CRI also filed two lawsuits accusing Integrated's
management of trying to entrench itself at the expense of the
limited partnership investors by changing the management
agreements.
   It isn't known what steps Integrated might take to try to
have CRI's proposed exchange offer ended. One option might be
for Integrated to ask the bankruptcy court to block the CRI
proposal. But the AIM partnerships themselves, which invest
in government-insured or guaranteed mortgages, aren't part of
the bankruptcy-law process and continue to operate.
   The four funds involved have about 64,000 investors.
Integrated receives income from managing the partnerships in
addition to its general partnership interest.
   The CRI proposal is "something we and Krupp are discussing
. . . right now," said Stephen D. Weinroth, Integrated
chairman. He didn't elaborate, but said that if CRI succeeds
in its proposed bid and unseats Integrated as the general
partner, "they would be obligated to give Integrated a
substantial amount of money" under the American Insured
partnership agreements for Integrated's partnership interests
in the funds, aside from management fees.
   Mr. Weinroth said he hasn't read the CRI complaint, but
said allegations that Integrated adopted "this cleverly
disguised poison pill are clearly untrue."
   A Krupp spokeswoman said she didn't know how or when the
issue might be resolved. There isn't a deadline for the pact
to be completed.
   Integrated manages more than 600 partnerships, and values
its assets at about $700 million. Mr. Weinroth said senior
creditors, who are owed about $1 billion, were told in
January they would receive about 45 to 50 cents on the
dollar. He said that figure remains "a proper valuation".
It's unclear what junior creditors, who are owed about $600
million, can expect.
   Although the auction set a minimum bid of $40 million
without conditions for the American Insured interests, CRI
said in its filing it was rebuffed in earlier efforts to
purchase the management entities from Integrated, including
an offer of $60 million in February. According to the filing,
Krupp in late May sought to have the court reduce the minimum
bid on the partnerships to $30 million. However, the pact
announced Friday calls for Integrated to receive an added
$6.5 million within a year after Krupps's $38.6 million
payment.
   Mr. Weinroth said Integrated hadn't turned down any offers
but he said CRI's $60 million offer involved substantial
deferred payments. The CRI proposal is conditioned on
Integrated reversing the change in its management contract.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0004
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0004.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Television:
   World War II a Perennial Ratings Winner
   ----
   By Dorothy Rabinowitz
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9
</SO>
<LP>
   On the sixth of June, some 10 days ago, a network
broadcaster noted that it was "the anniversary of D-Day, when
Allied forces invaded the continent of Europe during World
War II." This slightly jarring explanation served as a
reminder that, to a very large segment of the population, the
war is history of a long-gone era. To those who grew up in
the '30s and '40s, of course, it is nothing of the sort: To
this generation, the war is always here, always alive and
lurking just under the skin.
   But even this audience does not entirely account for a
phenomenon long evident to programmers in public television,
namely the existence of an insatiable public appetite for
World War II documentaries. Six years ago, Arts &amp;
Entertainment Network made a similar discovery when it began
broadcasting the films and the ratings soared. Network
representative Brook Bailey Johnson describes the response as
amazing: "What's particularly amazing is their repeatability.
People watch them over and over."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The two most popular are "Victory at Sea" and "The
Twentieth Century." The Churchill documentary, "The Valiant
Years," also has done very well, along with "Between the
Wars," "Air Power," "Crusade in Europe" (airing Wednesdays,
8:30-9 p.m. EDT, along with two related shows) and "Why We
Fight," Frank Capra's classic indoctrination film, made under
the auspices of the U.S. Army. The audience for this material
seems to grow and includes many young people.
   None of this is news to the people at public television.
Robert Kotlowitz, vice president for arts and humanities
programming at WNET, New York's PBS channel, notes: "Every
time we rerun `The World at War' or `Victory at Sea' we do as
well as the last time or better. We did `Shoah' -- which I
consider a World War II documentary -- in four parts and the
audience got bigger and bigger as the week went on. That was
true nationally, not just in New York." "The World at War"
comes in 13 parts, Mr. Kotlowitz says. "People just get
hooked on it, including young people. After all, what greater
story is there than World War II?"
   That it is a story whose ending everyone knows is not
irrelevant to its drawing power; expectation is greater than
surprise, Coleridge told us. The grimness of the first
installments is unrelenting. Still, despite the triumphant
German blitzkrieg, the Stukas bombing Warsaw, the Belgian's
face streaming tears as the invading Germans parade through
the streets -- despite the German officer on his horse,
smiling triumphant under the Arc de Triomphe as the Wehrmacht
units march past, despite the burning ships at Pearl Harbor,
one knows where this will all end. The footage ahead is of
mobilization, the long enlistment lines outside the induction
centers the day after Pearl Harbor, the destruction of the
Japanese fleet at Midway. Of the Allied troops packed into
boats on the coast of England, the fantastic armada bearing
down on Normandy the morning of June 6, 1944. The landing
craft door drops, a British soldier turns to look back, pats
the arm of the man in front, and with the rest lurches into
the water toward the spindly tall house on shore. To
generations of viewers, that soldier, that landing craft,
that tall house on shore, are the central images of D-Day. So
is the infantryman who falls at the shore's edge, and the
one, still walking, dragged out of the water by comrades.
   The footage to come is the liberation of Paris, the
assault on Berlin and the Reichstag, the long lines of
defeated Nazi soldiers trudging home. A cameraman recorded a
scene in "The World at War" -- at a newly liberated death
camp. It is of a British officer standing face to face with
the highest ranking Nazi officer in charge. The Nazi
commandant smiles and extends his arm to shake hands. The
British officer stares icily, refusing the hand. It is a
moment -- one, like so many in these films, that sums up the
moral passion of the war.
   It goes without saying that some documentaries of this
kind are better than others. After all, what can compete with
"The World at War" -- a work so formidable dramatically and
historically, and to top it off, narrated by Sir Laurence
Olivier. One can ask almost the same question about "Victory
at Sea," with its score by Richard Rodgers. Still, every one
of the documentaries draws from the same source -- World War
II combat footage -- which is why they are getting audiences.
   No movie about the period can equal the evocative power of
these grainy black-and-white clips. Not "The Longest Day,"
fine as it is, nor any other Hollywood film, particularly war
movies of the past 30 years. For one thing, the footage is
history unadulterated by revisionism, whereas a kind of
progressive political impulse seems to have unhinged movie
makers on the subject of the war in recent years. For
example, by way of atonement for Hollywood's representation
of our wartime Japanese enemies as buck-teethed runts, there
now appears to be an unwritten law that in current movies all
Japanese military personnel be depicted as not less than
six-foot-five, noble of visage, with Hyperion's curls, vast
sensitivity and learning. A mother could ask no more for her
daughter.
   Arts &amp; Entertainment plans to continue showing the war
documentaries, it says, until it gets signals that viewers
are losing interest. If that is the case it will likely be
showing those films into the indefinite future. In "The Great
Gatsby," the narrator refers to those who could, for the last
time in the world, look on something larger and more
significant than themselves. That, for so many in it and of
it, is the meaning of The War. The heroic moment of our
century. Not surprising that the wish to keep revisiting it
is unappeasable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0003
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0003.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Disney's `Dick Tracy' Nabs
   Solid Turnout at Opening
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   DIS TWX CRC PCI
</CO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   "Dick Tracy," Walt Disney Co.'s much ballyhooed summer
movie release, opened last weekend on about 2,300 screens
around the country with a solid, albeit not mind-numbing,
showing. It grossed between $22 million and $23 million,
Disney reported.
   Industry sources independently confirmed these preliminary
results. "It augurs very well for the film," said Martin
Grove, box office analyst for Baseline, an entertainment
information service. He noted that the three-day gross was a
Disney record. Last summer, "Batman" broke box-office records
with a $40.5 million opening weekend.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Three films vied for second place. Early indications were
that "Another 48 Hours," released by Paramount Communications
Inc.'s film unit, grossed about $10.4 million. And the
premiere of "Gremlins 2," from Time Warner Inc.'s Warner
Brothers unit, took in about $10.1 million. Carolco
Pictures's "Total Recall" apparently finished fourth at $9.8
million. Official tallies are due out today.
   Although Warner officials had been upset that Disney would
include in its figures the sales of $12 to $20 "Dick Tracy"
T-shirts that counted as admission tickets for special Friday
morning showings of the film, the marketing ploy apparently
didn't have much of an impact on the box-office race.
Industry sources attributed only about $1.25 million of
Disney's gross to the T-shirt sales.
   The key for the new films' staying power will be their
second weekend: As each new mega-hyped release opens, it has
knocked back its predecessor: "Back to the Future III"
dropped 43% in its second weekend; "Total Recall" dropped
41%. "Another 48 Hours" is expected to have dropped 47%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900618-0002
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900618-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Law -- Legal Beat:
   One of Failed Thrift's Firms to Pay
   $20 Million to Settle Investor Suits
   ----
   By Amy Dockser Marcus and Milo Geyelin
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   AMC FNM
</CO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
INSURANCE (INS)
BUILDING MATERIALS (BLD)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   A principal law firm of American Continental Corp. and its
Lincoln Savings &amp; Loan Association unit agreed to pay $20
million to settle suits filed by stockholders and bondholders
of the defunct thrift.
   In a statement released Friday, the New York law firm of
Kaye, Scholer, Fierman, Hays &amp; Handler said the settlement
represents less than two percent of the maximum total
recovery sought by the plaintiffs and is covered by the
firm's insurance policies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The law firm was an adviser to the thrift and Charles H.
Keating Jr., the former head of Lincoln and chairman of
American Continental.
   Almost 22,000 small investors purchased American
Continental bonds at the thrift's California branches. The
investors say they lost approximately $300 million when
American Continental collapsed and began operating under
Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code in April 1989. The
Lincoln Savings unit was seized by thrift regulators the same
month.
   The settlement covers all class action suits filed in
federal and California state courts. The allegations included
racketeering charges. The investors claimed they were
defrauded as a result of false financial statements made by
the thrift. The investors sought to recoup their losses from
Kaye Scholer and more than 60 other defendants, who they
allege bore some responsibility for the thrift's actions.
   "We are convinced that we committed no wrongdoing and are
not liable to anyone for the losses that have occurred," the
firm's statement said. The firm said it settled to avoid
protracted and costly litigation.
   Leonard Simon of Milberg Weiss Bershad Specthrie &amp; Lerach,
a lawyer for the plaintiffs, said the settlement represents a
"reasonable payment" by the law firm.
   One other defendant in the case has settled. In March, the
Los Angeles law firm of Parker, Milliken, Clark, O'Hara &amp;
Samuelian provisionally agreed to a settlement in which it
denied any wrongdoing. The arrangement calls for payment of
$4.3 million to the plaintiffs by the law firm's insurance
carriers and another $10 million in payments if that amount
isn't recouped from other defendants.
   ---
   REDLINING ALLEGATIONS against Fannie Mae are being
investigated.
   The U.S. Justice Department is investigating allegations
that the Federal National Mortgage Association has been
discriminating against lenders who want to finance
development projects in predominately black sections of St.
Louis.
   Prosecutors with the department's civil rights division
wrote Fannie Mae last month seeking records for all the
mortgages that it bought for multifamily developments in St.
Louis, and seven surrounding counties since 1985, according
to a copy of the letter.
   The agency responded with a list of 37 developments. None
involved conventional financing for projects in the St. Louis
area's predominately black neighborhoods.
   Fannie Mae is a federally chartered, publicly traded
company that operates a secondary market in mortgage loans.
It buys mortgages from lenders and packages some into
securities for sale to investors. The agency buys
approximately one in eight mortgage loans nationwide and
recently has been touting its commitment to help low-income,
moderate-income and middle-income Americans buy homes.
   A spokesman for Fannie Mae said it is cooperating with the
investigation and said it does not discriminate in any way. A
spokeswoman for the Justice Department declined to comment.
   The allegations first came to light in April, when St.
Louis developer Bruce Ring filed a suit in federal court
alleging that Fannie Mae and First Interstate Mortgage Co. of
Illinois, a local lender in St. Louis, were redlining in the
city's depressed northern section. Redlining is the practice
by which lenders reject loan applications in poor
neighborhoods. Mr. Ring's suit, the first in the country to
accuse Fannie Mae of redlining, is pending in U.S. District
Court in St. Louis.
   Mr. Ring claimed he applied to Fannie Mae through First
Interstate last August to refinance $3.6 million in
short-term loans so he could renovate seven run-down
apartment buildings in St. Louis. Five of the properties were
in North St. Louis. According to the suit, Fannie Mae turned
down the entire application after a First Interstate vice
president inspected the five sites and described them as
being in risky locations.
   The Justice Department has also written First Interstate
requesting "statistical data" on the mortgage company's
lending practices in St. Louis and surrounding counties.
Samuel C. Ebling, First Interstate's attorney, said he did
not comply.
   A spokesman for Fannie Mae said the company "does not
approve of or condone redlining and we carry out our business
in a way that reflects that."
   ---
   PAINT COMPANY SUES INSURERS for refusing to settle
products-liability suit.
   Cook Paint &amp; Varnish Co. is facing a $20 million jury
verdict that it says could have been avoided if its carriers
hadn't resisted negotiating a settlement. Conflicts over who
should pay such awards have long existed between an insured
defendant and its carriers, but recently suits alleging
damages for failure to settle have increased.
   "It's kind of a new trend in litigation," says Robert
Adams, an attorney in the Houston firm of Dunn, Kacal, Adams,
Pappas &amp; Law, counsel for St. Louis-based Safety Mutual
Casualty Corp., one of 10 insurance carriers named in the
case. The suit seeks $70 million in damages, including $50
million in punitive damages.
   Cook, a North Kansas City, Mo., paint manufacturer, was
held liable in a case brought by Allied Tank Services Inc., a
San Antonio, Texas, maker of drinking-water tanks. Allied
said it used Cook's paints to coat the interior of some of
its water tanks, but it alleged that the paint cracked and
bubbled, contaminating the water. Last week, a state court
jury in San Antonio found Cook negligent and awarded Allied
$20 million in damages.
   Thomas W. Wagstaff, an attorney with the Kansas City firm
of Blackwell Sanders Matheny Weary &amp; Lombardi, counsel for
Cook, said the Texas trial judge will be asked to set the
verdict aside. But in the meantime, he has sued the 10
carriers in state court in Liberty, Mo., alleging that they
acted in "bad faith." The suit says Cook demanded several
times that the carriers settle the Allied suit, but
defendants refused "even though the consequences . . . could
be devastating to Cook."
   Before trial, Mr. Wagstaff says, attorneys for Allied had
offered to settle their claims for $6.5 million, a figure he
contends could have been negotiated down to between $2
million and $3 million.
   Mr. Adams says many of the carriers weren't notified about
the Allied suit until it was being tried. They had
insufficient time to evaluate the extent of liability
coverage, whether the trial was being properly handled, or
whether it should be settled, he said.
   Also named as defendants are Missouri Insurance Guaranty
Association, St. Louis; Transport Indemnity Co., Los Angeles;
Fremont Indemnity Co., Los Angeles; International Insurance
Co., Chicago; Columbia Casualty Co., Chicago; International
Surplus Lines Insurance Co., Chicago; Constitution State
Insurance Co., Hartford; Granite State Insurance Co.,
Manchester, N.H.; and Union Insurance Co., Lincoln, Neb. They
either couldn't be reached or declined comment.
   Attorneys for Allied couldn't be reached for comment.
   ---
   A FORMER WEATHER UNDERGROUND radical is helping plan the
ABA's annual meeting.
   Bernardine Dohrn, who won notoriety two decades ago as a
revolutionary leader advocating "armed struggle" against the
U.S. government, will serve as program vice chair for the
American Bar Association's litigation section activities at
the August meeting, to be held in Chicago.
   Ms. Dohrn has been assisting the litigation section
program chairman for nearly a year in organizing panel
discussions and speeches. Topics to be discussed will range
from "The Ethical Example of Sir Thomas More" to "Using
Experts Cost-Effectively in Corporate Litigation."
   Ms. Dohrn spent the 1970s as a fugitive from
law-enforcement authorities. Soon after surfacing in 1980,
she was convicted of misdemeanor assault charges associated
with the 1969 "days of rage" demonstrations in Chicago. She
received a fine and was placed on probation. Ms. Dohrn worked
briefly at the New York office of Sidley &amp; Austin, but moved
to Chicago after her admission to the New York bar was held
up by its character committee. She is currently working in
Cook County's Office of the Public Guardian.
   Litigation program chairwoman Patricia Lee Refo said she
found Ms. Dohrn to be "a very capable person" and "a big help
in putting together the programs."
   ---
   THE STATE OF MASSACHUSETTS hired a law firm on a
contingency fee basis.
   Usually the state pays its outside lawyers on an hourly
basis. However, in a contingency arrangement, five attorneys
from the Boston law firm of Dangel &amp; de Benedictis, will act
as special assistant attorneys general in an asbestos case.
They are representing the state in a suit to recover the
costs of repairing asbestos-contaminated, state-owned
buildings. The defendants are asbestos manufacturers and
distributors. The firm will be paid on a sliding scale of no
more than 30% of the potential recovery, which has been
estimated at more than $100 million, according to a spokesman
for the state attorney general's office.
   The contingency fee arrangement is expected to be cheaper
for the state than hourly payments because if it looses, it
will not pay fees, and will incur no more than $2.5 million
for expenses.
   ---
   Wayne E. Green in Houston contributed to this article.
